article.description: Matt Freije scored a career-high 31 points, including 5-of-8 shooting from 3-point range, as Vanderbilt upset Georgia 94-91 Wednesday night.
article.headline: Freije's career-high 31 points pace Commodores
article.linkText: Vandy upsets No. 17 Georgia to end three-game skid
article.story: NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Vanderbilt Commodores apparently just needed some quality practices and a visit from the Georgia Bulldogs (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) to snap their three-game losing skid. Matt Freije scored a career-high 31 points, including 5-of-8 shooting from 3-point range, as Vanderbilt upset Georgia 94-91 Wednesday night. The Commodores (9-8, 2-4 Southeastern Conference) had not won since upsetting then-No. 4 Alabama on Jan. 11, and Freije said their confidence was down. "But we had three great practices before the game. That has been the pattern for us. We practice well, we've played well,'' Freije said. The Commodores played very well against Georgia (12-5, 4-2), outshooting the Bulldogs 57 percent to 51 percent. They trailed only twice, both in the first half, and led by as many as 17 in the second half. "Vanderbilt played great tonight,'' Georgia coach Jim Harrick said. "They deserved to win. They scored 94 points. No one else has done that against us. They played very well.'' Georgia hadn't allowed any opponent to score more than 83 points in a game this season. The Bulldogs came into the game having won 11 of their last 12, with the only loss coming on a buzzer beater at Florida on Jan. 11. But the Bulldogs never have had much luck in Nashville, let alone when they come into Memorial Gym ranked. Vanderbilt beat them for the fourth time in five visits when they've been ranked in the Top 25 and for the 44th time in 56 games here. This season, the Commodores are 2-5 against ranked opponents. "This just gives us some energy, and we were in desperate need of energy,'' Vanderbilt coach Kevin Stallings said. Vanderbilt led 81-71 with 4:12 left when the Bulldogs made a final push. Ezra Williams hit a 3-pointer, then scored on a dunk. Damien Wilkins hit a pair of free throws and then stole the ball despite playing with four fouls, and he scored on a wild layup that got Georgia to 83-80 with 2:38 left. That was as close as the Bulldogs got, as Vanderbilt hit 11-of-13 at the free-throw line in the final 1:33 to preserve the victory. Brian Thornton, who didn't take a shot in the first half, scored all 16 of his points in the second half for Vanderbilt. Mario Moore and Scott Hundley each had 14 as Vandy hit 9-of-16 from 3-point range. Williams led Georgia with 18 points. Jarvis Hayes and Rashad Wright each had 14 and Wilkins 13. Reserve Richard Wehunt, a former walk-on who had only 10 points all last season, had a career-high 16. Harrick blamed himself for playing Hayes too much. The junior forward strained his hip against Tennessee last week and played 33 minutes against Vandy. "He was not 100 percent,'' Stallings said. "Freije and Hundley fought hard to do a good job on him, but he was slowed considerably.'' The Commodores opened the game by hitting 17 of their first 30 shots. Freije had 19 in the first half as he hit his first four shots, including all three of his 3s. He scored 11 of Vandy's first 15 points in giving the Commodores a lead they held most of the first half. Harrick said Freije was magnificent. "Wilkins guarded him pretty well, but no one else did. He had a field day,'' Harrick said. Vanderbilt led by as many as 10, at 22-12, before the Bulldogs started getting back into the game. Wehunt had eight points in an 18-7 run, and Hayes hit a pair of free throws for a 30-29 lead with 6:21 left -- their first since the opening bucket. But Russell Lakey scored on a driving layup for the first of 10 unanswered points by Vanderbilt, and Georgia never led again. The Commodores held a 46-38 edge at halftime.
